node.text: Georgia back in 2017 was for sure the best experience in skiing I’ve ever had! Sharing so many rad moments with @samanthamatten and @leoslemett. node.text:
The moment when all I wanted and needed for the past year ended and all the pressure falls off in a second. An incredible feeling, impossible to put it in words.
But it wasn’t easy getting there...
At the 4th stop in Andorra I could have taken the title home only with the 6th place. Sure I took it serious but I was sure I had it. I was super consistent the past 3 comps with a 1st, 2nd and another 1st. Confidence boost.

Just before dropping in I changed my mind. I got cocky and didn’t want to win with a mellow run. I decided to add a backflip. I blacked out mid air like i never did before, crashed, and the title was gone for now. It would have been so incredibly nice to walk up to the finals at Verbier without pressure...
The two weeks leading up to Verbier was a nightmare. In case @kristoferturdell would win, i only had to become 10th. Sounds easy but when everyone expects you to win and you just had a stupid ass crash it’s a different story. I’m the guy that get’s motivation in proving people wrong, not right. And the fact that I wanted it so so much didn’t help.
Just once i arrived to Verbier, watching the last sun rays hit the Bec by myself i could calm down my nerves a bit and focus. Bib draw comes up, Kristofer Turdell, my only contender, had to drop a few places in front of me, good. I could watch him, and if he doesn’t make it onto the hotseat I’d automatically win.

After his run I got a call from @fabiostuder, telling me Kristofer is currently second. I started crying like a freaking baby. The mindfuck was over! Finally! I won!! Silly if I think of it now, but I was so damn happy.
I could finally enjoy my last run of the FWT season and fall in the arms of my friends at the finish line feeling 1000 tons lighter.
Thank you @freerideworldtour for this incredible season and everyone that made it special!! ❤️ Moving on lighthearted.
